{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503091"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:54:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:54:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1932"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1932"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.34,0.16,0.13,0.34,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1932"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55058"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1932"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1932"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40576"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"526"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3233"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3282"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16880"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55058"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 84-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of progressive and painless abdominal distension with constipation. This started two days after undergoing a laminectomy. She has not vomited and does not feel nauseated. She has a medical history of angina, atrial fibrillation, and osteoporosis. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears uncomfortable. Her pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 134/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is diffusely distended. There is no obvious tenderness, rigidity, or guarding on examination, and there are minimal bowel sounds present. Plain X-rays are ordered (Image 1, 2, 3).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sigmoid volvulus","Caecal volvulus","Toxic megacolon","Pseudo-obstruction","Pneumatosis coli"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe abdominal X-rays show a massively distended large bowel, with gaseous distension of all the colon down to and including the rectum. This is the pattern of a \u003Cstrong\u003Epseudo-obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E, which has led to her current symptoms. This is differentiated from a mechanical obstruction where there is often a \u0022transition point\u0022 where the bowel is often collapsed distal to the obstruction. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPseudo-obstruction is a functional disorder characterized by acute colonic dilatation without any mechanical obstruction. This patient is at risk for pseudo-obstruction due to her recent laminectomy and subsequent immobility. Other risk factors include electrolyte imbalances, medications (especially opioids and anticholinergics), and systemic illnesses. The condition results from an imbalance in the autonomic nervous system\u0027s regulation of colonic motility, leading to functional obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESigmoid volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the most common causes of bowel obstruction in an elderly patient; however, it is less likely given the probability of a pseudo-obstruction in the context of a recent surgery and immobility. Sigmoid volvulus may also show a coffee bean sign on abdominal X-ray, and loss of haustral folds.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EContrastingly, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecaecal volvulus\u003C/strong\u003E is more common in younger patients with an underlying cause such as adhesions or abdominal masses. It would also present with a large section of distended bowel on abdominal x-ray. In contrast to sigmoid volvulus, the colonic haustral pattern is likely to be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToxic megacolon\u003C/strong\u003E is a non-obstructive life-threatening condition characterised by systemic illness, diarrhoea, severe distension, and oedema of the bowel wall, and is most commonly associated with ulcerative colitis. It is a medical emergency due to the risk of imminent perforation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPneumatosis coli\u003C/strong\u003E is a radiographic description of intramural gas located in the colonic wall and is most commonly an incidental finding that is asymptomatic. It can be a precursor of serious conditions such as colonic ischaemia but is not a diagnosis alone, and must be taken into consideration with the clinical presentation of the patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of pseudo-obstruction typically involves supportive care, correction of any underlying electrolyte imbalances, and potentially neostigmine administration. In severe cases, colonoscopic decompression or surgery may be necessary.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pseudo-obstruction should be considered in patients with obstruction without an obvious cause of mechanical obstruction.","Recent surgery and immobility are risk factors for pseudo-obstruction.","Pseudo-obstruction is characterized by colonic dilatation without mechanical obstruction."],"references":["Wells CI, O\u0027Grady G, Bissett IP. Acute colonic pseudo-obstruction: A systematic review of aetiology and mechanisms. World J Gastroenterol. 2017 Aug 14;23(30):5634-5644. doi: 10.3748/wjg.v23.i30.5634. PMID: 28852322; PMCID: PMC5558126."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40576"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1932"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18383"},{"type":"media","id":"18384"},{"type":"media","id":"18385"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18383"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/11351da9-b924-4a0b-97fb-b25aec195f42.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/11351da9-b924-4a0b-97fb-b25aec195f42.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":593,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"18384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18384"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/71f6b905-a83f-4f43-bca7-f271e4070324.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/71f6b905-a83f-4f43-bca7-f271e4070324.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":593,"height":600}},{"type":"media","id":"18385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18385"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1fae9c22-10a2-4143-9249-56e99949017d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1fae9c22-10a2-4143-9249-56e99949017d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":638,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40576"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-13T08:35:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-13T08:35:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1932"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55058"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tag